DISCUSSION
Reconstitution of membrane proteins into liposomes is a widely used approach to study the structure and function of various proteins in the conditions mimicking natural environment. In this work, we have demonstrated that the usage of the lipophilic DiI dye during the preparation of LHCII proteoliposomes has proven to be a suitable method for labeling liposomes. It allowed them to be studied at the singleliposome level using TIRF and confocal microscopy. By implementing TIRF microscopy, we addressed efficiency of LHCII reconstitution into liposomes while by applying confocal microscopy, we were able to quantify the size of individual liposomes and the relative protein density therein. Particularly, the obtained results revealed that each of the density bands, which was supposed to be purified to some extend from free LHCII, still remained a highly heterogeneous mixture of empty liposomes, proteoliposomes of various sizes, and free LHCIIs. We found no gradient band consisting entirely of proteoliposomes. In any of given gradient density
